## What
Implement a `Daemon` builder struct that encapsulates the UNIX double-fork daemonization pattern. No external crate — we own the implementation. The API mirrors the ergonomics of the `daemonize` crate's builder but is our own code, using `libc` directly.

## File(s)
- `chesstty/chesstty/src/daemon.rs` (new)

## API Design (Builder Pattern)

```rust
use std::path::PathBuf;
use std::fs::File;

pub struct Daemon {
    pid_file: Option<PathBuf>,
    chown_pid_file: bool,
    working_directory: PathBuf,      // default: "/"
    user: Option<String>,
    group: Option<Group>,            // String name or u32 gid
    umask: u32,                      // default: 0o027
    stdout: Option<File>,
    stderr: Option<File>,
    privileged_action: Option<Box<dyn FnOnce() -> anyhow::Result<()>>>,
}

pub enum Group {
    Name(String),
    Id(u32),
}

impl Daemon {
    pub fn new() -> Self {
        Self {
            pid_file: None,
            chown_pid_file: false,
            working_directory: PathBuf::from("/"),
            user: None,
            group: None,
            umask: 0o027,
            stdout: None,
            stderr: None,
            privileged_action: None,
        }
    }

    pub fn pid_file(mut self, path: impl Into<PathBuf>) -> Self { self.pid_file = Some(path.into()); self }
    pub fn chown_pid_file(mut self, chown: bool) -> Self { self.chown_pid_file = chown; self }
    pub fn working_directory(mut self, path: impl Into<PathBuf>) -> Self { self.working_directory = path.into(); self }
    pub fn user(mut self, user: impl Into<String>) -> Self { self.user = Some(user.into()); self }
    pub fn group(mut self, group: impl Into<Group>) -> Self { self.group = Some(group.into()); self }
    pub fn umask(mut self, mask: u32) -> Self { self.umask = mask; self }
    pub fn stdout(mut self, f: File) -> Self { self.stdout = Some(f); self }
    pub fn stderr(mut self, f: File) -> Self { self.stderr = Some(f); self }
    pub fn privileged_action<F>(mut self, f: F) -> Self
    where F: FnOnce() -> anyhow::Result<()> + 'static {
        self.privileged_action = Some(Box::new(f));
        self
    }

    /// Execute the double-fork daemonization sequence.
    ///
    /// On success, returns Ok(()) in the daemon (grandchild) process.
    /// The original caller process exits via std::process::exit(0).
    ///
    /// Sequence:
    /// 1. First fork — parent exits
    /// 2. setsid() — detach from controlling terminal
    /// 3. Execute privileged_action (if set) — runs before privilege drop
    /// 4. Drop privileges (user/group, if set)
    /// 5. Second fork — session leader exits
    /// 6. umask + chdir
    /// 7. Redirect stdin→/dev/null, stdout/stderr→configured files
    /// 8. Write PID file (grandchild PID)
    pub fn start(self) -> anyhow::Result<()> { ... }
}
```

### Usage in the shim (chesstty/src/daemon.rs caller)
```rust
let stdout = File::create("/tmp/chesstty-server.out")?;
let stderr = File::create("/tmp/chesstty-server.err")?;

Daemon::new()
    .pid_file(config.pid_path())
    .working_directory("/tmp")
    .umask(0o027)
    .stdout(stdout)
    .stderr(stderr)
    .start()?;

// We are now the daemon — start tokio runtime and run server
tokio::runtime::Runtime::new()?.block_on(server::run())?;
```

### Implementation Notes
- Reference `daemonize` crate source (https://github.com/knsd/daemonize) for edge cases
- `impl Into<Group>` for both `&str`/`String` and `u32` to support `.group("daemon")` and `.group(2)`
- `privileged_action` runs between setsid and privilege drop — useful for binding sockets that need elevated permissions
- `chown_pid_file`: if true and user/group set, chown the PID file after writing
- File descriptor redirection via `libc::dup2()`: stdin→/dev/null, stdout→stdout file, stderr→stderr file
- If stdout/stderr not configured, redirect to /dev/null
- Consider closing inherited FDs (3..max_fd) to prevent leaking parent's open files
- All `unsafe` blocks (fork, setsid, umask, dup2, setuid, setgid) require `// SAFETY:` comments
- `start()` consumes self (moved, not borrowed) — one-shot operation

### Error Type
Consider a dedicated `DaemonError` enum (via thiserror) rather than stringly-typed anyhow errors:
```rust
#[derive(Debug, thiserror::Error)]
pub enum DaemonError {
    #[error("first fork failed: {0}")]
    ForkFailed(std::io::Error),
    #[error("setsid failed: {0}")]
    SetsidFailed(std::io::Error),
    #[error("failed to write PID file: {0}")]
    PidFile(std::io::Error),
    #[error("privilege drop failed: {0}")]
    PrivilegeDrop(std::io::Error),
    #[error("privileged action failed: {0}")]
    PrivilegedAction(anyhow::Error),
    // ...
}
```

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] `Daemon` struct with builder-pattern API (all setters return Self)
- [ ] Every method except `new()` and `start()` is optional with sensible defaults
- [ ] Double-fork implemented correctly (parent exits, grandchild is daemon)
- [ ] setsid() detaches from controlling terminal
- [ ] Second fork prevents re-acquiring controlling terminal
- [ ] privileged_action runs between setsid and privilege drop
- [ ] User/group privilege drop via setuid/setgid (when configured)
- [ ] PID file written with daemon's actual PID (grandchild)
- [ ] PID file optionally chowned to target user/group
- [ ] stdin→/dev/null, stdout/stderr→configured files (or /dev/null)
- [ ] Dedicated DaemonError enum (thiserror), not stringly-typed errors
- [ ] All unsafe blocks have // SAFETY comments
- [ ] Works on macOS (darwin) and Linux
- [ ] No external daemonize crate in dependencies

## What
Wire up the complete default-mode lifecycle in the chesstty shim: check if server is running → if not, daemonize it → wait for socket → launch TUI in the foreground.

## File(s)
- `chesstty/chesstty/src/main.rs` — default command handler
- `chesstty/chesstty/src/launch.rs` (new) — launch orchestration

## Implementation Details
```rust
pub async fn launch_default() -> anyhow::Result<()> {
    let config = config::RuntimeConfig::load();

    // 1. Check if server is already running
    if process::is_server_running(&config.pid_path) {
        tracing::info!("Server already running (PID file: {:?})", config.pid_path);
    } else {
        // 2. Clean up any stale state
        process::remove_stale_pid(&config.pid_path)?;
        if config.socket_path.exists() {
            std::fs::remove_file(&config.socket_path)?;
        }

        // 3. Daemonize the server
        tracing::info!("Starting server daemon...");
        daemon::start_server_daemon(&config)?;
    }

    // 4. Wait for socket to become ready
    tracing::info!("Waiting for server socket...");
    wait::wait_for_socket(
        &config.socket_path,
        config.socket_timeout,
        config.poll_interval,
    ).await?;

    // 5. Launch TUI in foreground
    tracing::info!("Launching TUI...");
    // Either:
    // a) Call client-tui as a library: client_tui::run_app(config.socket_path).await
    // b) Exec into the client-tui binary: std::process::Command::new("client-tui")
    // Prefer (a) for better integration
    Ok(())
}
```

### Decision: Library vs Exec for TUI launch
**Recommended: Library call.** Import client-tui's run function and call it directly. This avoids PATH issues, version skew, and gives better error propagation. Requires client-tui to expose a public `run_app(socket_path)` function.

### Decision: Daemonize boundary
The daemonize call forks the process. The parent (shim) continues to step 4. The child (daemon) starts the tokio runtime and runs the server. The shim must NOT have started a tokio runtime before forking — use `std::process::Command` or `daemonize` in a sync context, then start the async runtime for the wait+TUI phase.

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] `cargo run -p chesstty` (no args) starts server daemon and launches TUI
- [ ] If server is already running, skips daemon launch and goes straight to TUI
- [ ] Stale PID/socket files are cleaned up before new server launch
- [ ] TUI connects to server via UDS after socket is ready
- [ ] Clear error message if server fails to start within timeout
- [ ] Server continues running after TUI exits (daemon persists)
- [ ] Tracing logs show each lifecycle step

## What
Add SIGTERM and SIGINT signal handling to the server so it shuts down gracefully: stops accepting new requests, completes in-flight RPCs, cleans up Stockfish child processes, removes the PID file and socket file, and exits cleanly.

## File(s)
- `server/src/main.rs` — wrap serve in tokio::select! with signal handler
- `server/src/shutdown.rs` (new) — shutdown coordination logic
- `server/src/session/manager.rs` — ensure SessionManager propagates shutdown to actors

## Implementation Details
```rust
use tokio::signal::unix::{signal, SignalKind};

let mut sigterm = signal(SignalKind::terminate())?;
let mut sigint = signal(SignalKind::interrupt())?;

tokio::select! {
    result = server.serve_with_incoming(uds_stream) => {
        result?;
    }
    _ = sigterm.recv() => {
        tracing::info!("Received SIGTERM, shutting down gracefully");
    }
    _ = sigint.recv() => {
        tracing::info!("Received SIGINT, shutting down gracefully");
    }
}

// Cleanup sequence:
// 1. Stop accepting new connections
// 2. Wait for in-flight RPCs to complete (with timeout)
// 3. Shut down SessionManager (kills Stockfish subprocesses)
// 4. Remove PID file
// 5. Remove socket file
```

Consider using `tokio::sync::watch` to broadcast shutdown signal to all subsystems. The existing `CleanupGuard` (Drop-based) pattern for sessions should integrate with this.

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Server handles SIGTERM and shuts down within 5 seconds
- [ ] Server handles SIGINT (Ctrl+C) and shuts down gracefully
- [ ] PID file is removed on graceful shutdown
- [ ] Socket file is removed on graceful shutdown
- [ ] All Stockfish child processes are terminated on shutdown
- [ ] In-flight RPCs complete before server exits (with timeout)
- [ ] Server logs shutdown sequence via tracing

## What
Implement the `engine stop` subcommand that reads the PID file and sends the appropriate signal to the server. Also add integration tests covering all lifecycle edge cases.

## File(s)
- `chesstty/chesstty/src/stop.rs` (new) — stop command implementation
- `chesstty/chesstty/src/main.rs` — wire stop handler to CLI dispatch
- `chesstty/chesstty/tests/integration.rs` (new) — integration tests

## Implementation Details

### Graceful Stop (default)
```rust
pub fn stop_server(pid_path: &Path, force: bool) -> anyhow::Result<()> {
    let pid = process::read_pid(pid_path)?;

    if force {
        tracing::warn!("Force-killing server (PID {pid})");
        unsafe { libc::kill(pid, libc::SIGKILL); }
    } else {
        tracing::info!("Sending SIGTERM to server (PID {pid})");
        unsafe { libc::kill(pid, libc::SIGTERM); }

        // Wait for process to exit (poll with timeout)
        let deadline = Instant::now() + Duration::from_secs(10);
        while Instant::now() < deadline {
            if unsafe { libc::kill(pid, 0) } != 0 {
                tracing::info!("Server stopped");
                break;
            }
            std::thread::sleep(Duration::from_millis(100));
        }

        // If still running after timeout, warn user
        if unsafe { libc::kill(pid, 0) } == 0 {
            tracing::warn!("Server did not stop within 10s. Use --force to kill.");
            anyhow::bail!("Server did not stop gracefully");
        }
    }

    // Clean up stale files
    process::remove_stale_pid(pid_path)?;
    let socket_path = config::socket_path();
    if socket_path.exists() {
        std::fs::remove_file(&socket_path)?;
    }

    Ok(())
}
```

### Integration Test Scenarios
1. **Server already running** — default launch skips daemon, connects TUI
2. **Stale PID file** — dead process, shim cleans up and launches new server
3. **Socket wait timeout** — server fails to start, shim reports clear error
4. **Graceful stop** — SIGTERM, server cleans up, files removed
5. **Force stop** — SIGKILL, shim cleans up stale files
6. **Double stop** — `engine stop` when server not running → clean error
7. **No PID file** — `engine stop` with no server → clean error

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] `chesstty engine stop` sends SIGTERM and waits for server exit
- [ ] `chesstty engine stop --force` sends SIGKILL immediately
- [ ] Clean error message when no server is running
- [ ] Clean error message when PID file doesn't exist
- [ ] Stale PID/socket files are cleaned up after stop
- [ ] Integration tests cover all 7 scenarios above
- [ ] `unsafe` blocks for libc::kill are minimal and well-documented

## What
Migrate server and client from TCP `[::1]:50051` to Unix Domain Socket communication. The server binds a UDS listener, and the client connects via UDS. This is prerequisite for the shim to manage the server as a local daemon.

## File(s)
- `server/src/main.rs` — replace `.serve(addr)\ with `.serve_with_incoming(uds_stream)`
- `server/Cargo.toml` — add tokio-stream dependency
- `chess-client/src/client.rs` — add UDS connect method using tower connector
- `chess-client/Cargo.toml` — add hyper-util, tower deps (already has tower 0.5, hyper 1.5)
- `client-tui/src/main.rs` — update connection to use UDS path

## Implementation Details

### Server UDS Binding
```rust
use tokio::net::UnixListener;
use tokio_stream::wrappers::UnixListenerStream;

// Clean up stale socket file
let socket_path = config::socket_path();
if socket_path.exists() {
    std::fs::remove_file(&socket_path)?;
}

let uds = UnixListener::bind(&socket_path)?;
let uds_stream = UnixListenerStream::new(uds);

Server::builder()
    .add_service(ChessServiceServer::new(service))
    .serve_with_incoming(uds_stream)
    .await?;
```

### Client UDS Connection (tonic snippet)
```rust
use hyper_util::rt::TokioIo;
use tokio::net::UnixStream;
use tonic::transport::{Channel, Endpoint, Uri};
use tower::service_fn;

let channel = Endpoint::try_from("http://[::]:50051")?
    .connect_with_connector(service_fn(move |_: Uri| {
        let path = socket_path.clone();
        async move {
            Ok::<_, std::io::Error>(TokioIo::new(UnixStream::connect(path).await?))
        }
    }))
    .await?;
let client = ChessServiceClient::new(channel);
```

Note: The Endpoint URI is a dummy — tonic requires it but the connector ignores it.

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Server binds to UDS at configured socket path (default /tmp/chesstty.sock)
- [ ] Server removes stale socket file before binding
- [ ] Client connects to server via UDS (not TCP)
- [ ] All 25 gRPC RPCs work over UDS (existing tests pass)
- [ ] Socket file is created with appropriate permissions
- [ ] `tokio-stream` (net feature) added to server deps
- [ ] TCP fallback is NOT required (clean migration)
